	<rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">see the comment in "is motivation for"</rdfs:comment>
	<rdfs:isDefinedBy rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/54i#"/>
	<rdfs:label xml:lang="en">is motivated by</rdfs:label>
	<skos:altLabel xml:lang="en">has motivation</skos:altLabel>
</rdf:Description>

<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/54i#isMotivationFor">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#ObjectProperty"/>
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#TransitiveProperty"/>
	<rdfs:domain rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/54i#Motivation"/>
	<rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Strictly speaking something can only be a motivation for an Agent, or in fact - only for a Person. However, the choice is to use isMotivationFor in a broader sense so that why-chains can be traced. For example, using the inverse property, if &lt;this&gt; isMotivatedBy &lt;reason1&gt;, which isMotivatedBy &lt;reason2&gt;, it seems useful to infer that &lt;reason2&gt; isMotivationFor &lt;this&gt;, which is achieved by declaring isMotivatedFor as transitive property.</rdfs:comment>
	<rdfs:isDefinedBy rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/54i#"/>
	<rdfs:label xml:lang="en">is motivation for</rdfs:label>
</rdf:Description>

