</rdf:Description>

<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/54i#Time">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class"/>
	<rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">An individual member of class Temporal can have  one or two data-properties.
In the first case it refers to a point in time, in the second - to a period (or interval - see the difference in the comment of http://data.europa.eu/54i#hasPeriod), defined by periodStart and periodEnd.

All three properties have their domain declared as member of class Temporal. This means that, if one of these properties is used by members of other classes, that member will be inferred as member of the Temporal class. The purpose is to be able query all temporal information from that single class.

All three properties are declared as  functional. This means, each individual will have only one property of the kind.</rdfs:comment>
	<rdfs:isDefinedBy rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/54i#"/>
	<rdfs:label xml:lang="en">Time</rdfs:label>
	<skos:altLabel xml:lang="en">Temporal</skos:altLabel>
</rdf:Description>

<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://data.europa.eu/54i#Transformation">
	<rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class"/>
	<rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Transformation in this sense can be used at any level. When used for small transformations such as to switch on a computer or to delete a file, its synonyms could be “action”, “task”, and “activity”. When transformation refers to a set of sequential actions, the common preference is to call it a “process”. “Activity” is also sometimes used for a bigger set of actions. Last, transformation can refer to such a big set of transition as “organisational transformation”.   

Note on the preference of "Transformation" label over "Process" in ECCF:  
The concept of "Process" suggests processing, sequence of activities. The focus is on the flow and on the activities, not on why they are performed. "Transformation" begs the question "of what" and "for what". In addition, it further focuses more on the change of states, as captured by events, which can be observed, detected, recorded in a way that is less a matter of opinion.  

“By a state of a system is meant any well-defined condition or property that can be recognised if it occurs again.” (R. Ashby) 

Another reason to prefer Transformation is that it does not imply granularity and can be used recursively, while task, activity, sub-process and process cannot. Furthermore, "Transformation" can be applied in the same way to Activity and to an Event. For example, the state of a CatchMessageEvent (in the sense used in BPMN) is transformed from "waiting" to '"message</rdfs:comment>
	<rdfs:isDefinedBy rdf:resource="http://data.europa.eu/54i#"/>
	<rdfs:label xml:lang="en">Transformation</rdfs:label>
	<skos:altLabel xml:lang="en">Process</skos:altLabel>
</rdf:Description>

